column169: Clean Harbors was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, personnel observed that the released material impacted the trailer and an 8’-by-3’ area of roadway. They confirmed that two (2) gallons of material was released from one (1) 55-gallon drum due to being punctured while being loaded by the customer. There was one (1) drum of product involved in this release. After assessing the roadway, the truck was taken back to a terminal for additional cleaning. Clean Harbors personnel containerized the remaining product into one drum to be shipped on. They then overpacked the damaged drum into one (1) 85-gallon metal drum and used one (1) 55-gallon metal drum to containerize the spent absorbents used in the cleaning of the trailer. Clean Harbors personnel staged the generated waste onsite before departing. The generated waste will remain onsite for the ESTES team to coordinate disposal.

SET Environmental was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, they observed an estimated (1) gallon of material released from one (1) 330-gallon plastic tote that was cracked at the top of the tote from improper preparation for shipping. SET Environmental personnel observed that the released material impacted 3 ft-by-2 ft of trailer and concrete dock floor. SET Environmental personnel deployed granular absorbents to the impacted area and containerized them along with the cut-up tote and PPE into two (2) 55-gallon poly drums. The remaining material in the product tote was to be transferred to two (2) 275-gallon IBC tote. Generated waste was staged onsite at the terminal prior to the contractor demobilization. The generated waste will remain onsite for the Dayton Freight Lines team to coordinate disposal.

column169: On March 6, 202, at 0900 ET, Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) was contacted by Day & Ross personnel in Winnipeg, Manitoba regarding the release of Sodium Bisulfite Solution. Contractors were dispatched to the site to perform all onsite clean-up activities. Upon arrival, contractors confirmed the release of 10.5 gallons of Sodium Bisulfite Solution (UN2693, 8, III) from (1) 275-gallon poly tote onto the concrete dock. The release was due to a screw protruding from the bottom of the pallet that punctured the tote underneath, impacting a 10’ x 10’ area of the concrete dock. No drains or waterways were found to be impacted by the release. The release was cleaned with absorbents and the proper PPE. All waste generated from addressing this release was containerized in (2) 55-gallon DFs which were staged onsite, along with the damaged tote, by contractors for proper disposal.

column44: BONDERITE C-AK ZX-1 ALKALINE CLEANER (PARCO CLEANER ZX-1)
column169: XPO-Logistics contacted ERTS regarding a punctured tote containing hazardous product, BONDERITE C-AK ZX-1 ALKALINE CLEANER. A contractor dispatched and observed an estimated 200-gallon release onto the concrete dock floor and parking lot in a 100’x70’ area as a result of a forklift puncture. Oil dry was applied to the released material and a tote transfer was performed for the residual product left inside of the damaged tote. In total, 23 drums of waste were generated from this response that were taken by the contractor and staged at their location for waste management. The customer refused the new tote with the transferred product, so XPO staged the tote in the waste area for waste disposal. No storm-drains, waterways, or soil were involved in this incident.

column169: GATX 28473 was found in the Dayton, TX yard leaking from the manway when the car was moved on 3/3/2025. A BNSF Contractor was dispatched, investigated GATX 28473 and determined the release was due to a bad manway gasket and 3 of 6 manway bolts less than tool tight.
